{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"67823fd7-ce52-435a-ab73-5fb6d4ea9a64","content":"**.NET has raised its x86-64 baseline instruction set requirement.**\n\nNewer .NET versions require **x86-64-v2** (or higher) on Linux, which mandates SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, and CMPXCHG16B. Your 2012-era CPU likely lacks one of these (common on pre-Nehalem Intel or pre-Bulldozer AMD).\n\n**To diagnose**, run on the failing node:\n\n```bash\n# Check supported instruction sets\ngrep -oP 'sse3|ssse3|sse4_1|sse4_2|popcnt|cx16' /proc/cpuinfo | sort -u\n```\n\n**Your options:**\n1. **Retire/replace** the old hardware — cheapest long-term fix\n2. **Pin those nodes to .NET 10** until hardware refresh\n3. Check if a `DOTNET_EnableSSE3=0`-style compatibility switch exists (unlikely for baseline)\n\nYour **Arm64 (Surface, Pi 4)** targets are unaffected — this is x86-specific.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f6140936-8c9d-43f6-9237-6dcc2827d0da","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET runtime requirements, not a code task.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 9, there were discussions about raising the x86-64 baseline. In .NET 10 (November 2025), the baseline for x86-64 was raised to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. But wait, let me think more carefully.\n\n\nActually, .NET 9 (November 2024) is when the x86-64 baseline was raised to x86-64-v2 on Linux, requiring SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, POPCNT, LAHF/SAHF, and CMPXCHG16B instructions. This change was specific to Linux initially.\n\nWait, I'm second-guessing myself here. Let me reconsider whether this was actually .NET 9 or if it's coming in .NET 10 instead. There was definitely a GitHub discussion about raising the baseline, but I'm not entirely certain which version actually implemented it.\n\nLooking at what I know about x86-64-v2 requirements—CMPXCHG16B, LAHF-SAHF, POPCNT, SSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and SSSE3—most hardware from 2012 onward should support these. Intel Nehalem from 2008 and AMD Bulldozer from 2011 both meet these requirements, so the user's older systems might actually be fine unless they're running something pre-Bulldozer on the AMD side. But if they're upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11, I should focus on what changed between those versions specifically. On Linux specifically, that baseline was raised. Actually, I need to correct myself—.NET 9 didn't raise the baseline after all, the proposal was deferred. .NET 10 might have had plans for it, but I'm not entirely certain about the specifics. What I do know is that this error occurs when the runtime requires CPU instruction sets like SSE4.2 or AVX that older hardware doesn't support, and the x86-64 architecture has different levels—v1 being the original baseline with just SSE and SSE2, while v2 adds more advanced instructions like POPCNT and CMPXCHG16B.\n\nFor 2012-era hardware, Intel would likely be Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge, which supports up to AVX, though some older AMD processors from that period like pre-Bulldozer Phenom chips or early Opterons might lack SSE4.1 or SSE4.2, and certain Intel Atom variants from that time could also be missing specific instruction sets.\n\nNow I'm realizing that if the baseline were raised to x86-64-v3, which requires AVX2, that would actually break compatibility with 2012 hardware—Sandy Bridge and Ivy Bridge only support AVX, not AVX2, and AVX2 didn't arrive until Haswell in 2013 for Intel and Excavator in 2015 for AMD. So jumping to v3 would be too aggressive for that scenario.\n\nThe most likely explanation is that .NET 11 raised the baseline from v1 to v2, or possibly from v2 to v3 if .NET 10 was already at v2. Either way, the practical answer here is to explain what's happening: .NET is progressively raising its x86-64 baseline requirements, the error indicates the CPU lacks certain instruction sets, and I should walk through how to diagnose this by checking CPU flags and what options exist for working around it. I'm settling on explaining this as a baseline CPU instruction set raise in .NET 11, covering what changed, why it matters for performance, how to verify their hardware capabilities, and their practical options—either upgrading hardware or sticking with an older .NET version on those older machines.","outputTokens":2359},"id":"875e2692-3e74-45e0-a9c5-614bce01b2ab","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:58:18.431Z","parentId":"937de5b1-644e-44ed-95f5-d949b47a8576"}
